@article{leachSystemsViewEmotion2021,
	title = {A {Systems} {View} of {Emotion} in {Socio}-political {Context}},
	volume = {2},
	issn = {2662-2041, 2662-205X},
	url = {https://link.springer.com/10.1007/s42761-021-00051-z},
	doi = {10.1007/s42761-021-00051-z},
	abstract = {Most work to date in psychology and related sciences has examined simple, unidirectional causal processes of emotion affecting socio-political context or vice versa. In this classic, mechanistic view of science, each empirical observation stands on its own as a piece of some grander, not yet understandable, puzzle of nature. There have been repeated calls to eschew classic approaches in favor of systems meta-theory in psychology and related sciences. In this paper, we join these calls by arguing that systems meta-theory can better enable the study of emotions in socio-political contexts. We offer a brief primer on systems meta-theory, delineating three key beneficial features: multi-leveled, complex, and dynamic. Viewing emotion as a system of systems—within the person, their relationships (to others), and within the world (locally and globally)—enables fresh theory, method, and statistical analysis well suited to the study of emotion in a socio-political context.},
	language = {en},
	number = {4},
	urldate = {2022-06-03},
	journal = {Affective Science},
	author = {Leach, Colin Wayne and Bou Zeineddine, Fouad},
	month = dec,
	year = {2021},
	keywords = {complex systems, complexity, emotion complexity, emotion theory, read, review/meta-analysis},
	pages = {353--362},
	annote = {Summary: great paper, reading recommendation!
The authors argue that emotions need to be viewed and researched as a system of systems. They give a brief review of systems meta-theory and try to map the three major attributes (multi-leveled, causally complex, and dynamic) onto common emotion theories.

Systems Meta-theory
1. Systems are multileveled= “According to the meta-theory there are multiple systems, at different levels of abstraction or of analysis, nested within a larger system.”


Macro-level systems


physical structures, natural and geographical boundaries, and political, economic, and other institutions (culture, structure, institutions)


emotion has been studied in macro-level systems by sociology and anthropology




Meso-level systems




bridges between macro and meso, depending on the context


smaller collectives, relationships, such as couple, family, co-workers


“meso-level emotional climate or feeling norm of the collective can influence how individual members experience and express emotion via shared appraisal or feeling, social contagion, and dyadic synchronization”

Micro-level systems


systems within the individual


these systems are the most frequently examined in work on emotion (psychology): perception, attention, memory, etc.


these work together in a system






-{\textgreater} these systems don’t just operate at different levels, they affect each other in complex and dynamic ways
2. Systems are complex= “Systems meta-theory assumes that systems at multiple levels operate together in a complex (rather than simple, unidirectional, linear, mechanistic) way. This complexity is achieved because the component parts of each of the relevant systems, and thus the overarching system, is “self-organizing”[..]. The parts combine to produce an invisible whole that works to do what cannot be done by the parts on their own”.


each system within a system is semi-autonomous


a system of systems is redundant, they can produce a phenomenon in multiple ways


structure and logic are less apparent, but the combination/product is clear



3. Systems are dynamic= “Systems meta-theory presumes that phenomena exist in non-equilibrium states that may appear stable but are always changing (even if only to maintain the status quo).”


dynamic in time, across persons, across contexts


change is often non-linear, and even chaotic


results in heterogeneous empirical observations which high levels of randomness


e.g., through fixed and random effects structures; especially when including non-linearity in their analysis





Emotion Systems


emotions experienced on the micro-level may be different depending on the meso- and macro-level; “emotion as rooted in interactions, relationships, and culture suggests that the social and psychological meaning most central to a particular emotion is variable”


emotion regulation research suggests a dynamic process by which individuals aim to alter what, where, and for how long they experience an emotion


emotion as an emergent phenomenon (Barrett’s constructionist theory): self-organized system that produces affect (on a physical level), then another cognitive system that helps understanding the meaning of the affective system


cognitive appraisal: emotion as a an emergent phenomenon produced by the interplay between numerous complex systems



Emotion in Socio-political Context


Social Identity Model of Collective Action (SIMCA): micro-level explanations tied to group biases: social identity as a member of a group that suffers societal injustice is a partial basis for displeasure at believing injustice and a sense of (political or group) efficacy -{\textgreater} unidirectional, but there are feedback loops, e.g., the individual motivation to protest -{\textgreater} feedback loops in a process are always a good sign that a systems approach is warranted (Fig. 3)


“Rather than assuming that emotion- and problem-focused coping are solely micro-level individual processes, the model presumes that social support from like-minded others (at the meso-level) can be an important basis for emotion and a sense of (collective, political) efficacy.” (Leach and Bou Zeineddine, 2021, p. 357)”


“Reinka and Leach (2018) analyzed their data with mixed-effects models that could distinguish the effects of stimuli, stimuli type, individual, and individual’s group in ways that helped to identify the system likely in play for each effect.” (Leach and Bou Zeineddine, 2021, p. 359)



“As it is not always possible to examine systems at very distant levels in a single study, a multi-method project can rely on common concepts from a more general theory embedded within a systems meta-theory.” (Leach and Bou Zeineddine, 2021, p. 359)

Conclusion
“In other words, systems meta-theory demands that work on emotion in a socio-political context theorizes explicitly and formally how systems of emotion and context combine to produce phenomena of interest.” (Leach and Bou Zeineddine, 2021, p. 359)


multi-leveled methods and statistics


dynamic study of phenomenon intensively over time as well as over people and contexts


multiple methods used together to provide a more complex combination of forms of empirical observation



data


